00:38:11.996 --> 00:38:15.746
These trees there that spray sap
in all the cars for some reason,

00:38:15.876 --> 00:38:17.476
and I'm not sure, you know, why.

00:38:17.476 --> 00:38:21.196
But I was walking into work and
I saw the texture on the side

00:38:21.196 --> 00:38:23.036
and I just stared at it,
like, you know, weirdo.

00:38:23.186 --> 00:38:23.756
I'm like, wow.

00:38:24.426 --> 00:38:25.616
That texture looks really cool.

00:38:25.616 --> 00:38:26.726
I'm not sure what I'm
going to use it for.

00:38:26.726 --> 00:38:29.596
So I took the picture and then
I realized it was actually this

00:38:29.646 --> 00:38:33.816
really perfect way to transition
from the organic leather

00:38:33.816 --> 00:38:36.466
on the front of her face
to the more hardened shells

00:38:36.466 --> 00:38:37.336
on the side of her head.

00:38:37.686 --> 00:38:40.666
So, I really loved it for
that particular purpose.

00:38:40.666 --> 00:38:41.926
Though when I took the
picture, I had no idea

00:38:41.926 --> 00:38:45.086
when I was going to use it.

00:38:45.266 --> 00:38:48.706
Again, I'm trying to get sort
of this material transition

00:38:48.706 --> 00:38:51.136
because we're talking about
two different textures here.

00:38:53.456 --> 00:38:54.786
This, again, is one
of my favorite parts

00:38:54.786 --> 00:38:58.466
because I can really paint in
as much detail as I would like.

00:38:59.196 --> 00:39:02.706
Now, so we've got these shapes
and it's starting to feel good

00:39:02.706 --> 00:39:04.466
but it's still in the realm

00:39:04.466 --> 00:39:06.886
of being a bit too
photorealistic, right?

00:39:06.926 --> 00:39:10.036
We could be moving into Uncanny
Valley here if I'm not careful

00:39:10.236 --> 00:39:12.616
with all of this photo
detail that I'm using.

00:39:12.616 --> 00:39:16.296
And so, the next thing that
I would do is actually start

00:39:16.296 --> 00:39:20.146
to paint on top of this
to really nail the details

00:39:20.146 --> 00:39:23.276
down the way that-- the way
that it was in the art packet.

00:39:24.836 --> 00:39:27.126
So, let's see.

00:39:27.486 --> 00:39:31.176
I remember from the packet there
were these really graphic shapes

00:39:31.176 --> 00:39:31.876
around her eyes.

00:39:31.876 --> 00:39:33.276
I'm going to try
and pull those out.

00:39:33.666 --> 00:39:35.986
Again, like I said, I'm
going pretty darn fast here.

00:39:35.986 --> 00:39:43.716
So, I apologize I'm being a
bit sloppy in how I do this.

00:39:43.936 --> 00:39:46.116
Once I've painted kind
of on top of this,

00:39:46.116 --> 00:39:48.926
it starts to make
it feel more graphic

00:39:48.926 --> 00:39:51.836
and make it feel a
bit more painterly

00:39:51.836 --> 00:39:53.946
and less creature-shop.

00:39:54.636 --> 00:39:58.556
I'm just trying to get
in some of these folds.

00:39:59.366 --> 00:40:02.936
I'm going to get some
great crow's feet

00:40:02.936 --> 00:40:03.556
on the side of her face.

00:40:03.866 --> 00:40:06.096
It's funny because, shaders,
we always love to work

00:40:06.096 --> 00:40:09.396
on old characters because their
faces really tell a story.

00:40:10.306 --> 00:40:13.176
You can see, you know, the most
common expression a person has

00:40:13.176 --> 00:40:13.986
had for their whole life.

00:40:14.616 --> 00:40:17.346
You know, if you frown a
lot, those lines are kind

00:40:17.346 --> 00:40:19.206
of etched permanently
into your face.

00:40:19.846 --> 00:40:23.186
And with older characters,
I actually get to take part

00:40:23.186 --> 00:40:25.886
in telling the story by what
the character looks like.

00:40:26.006 --> 00:40:29.816
And that was-- you know, my goal
here is I-- with Hardscrabble,

00:40:29.816 --> 00:40:33.386
I really wanted her to look
as good as this character was,

00:40:33.386 --> 00:40:35.046
I mean, because she's
such an awesome character

00:40:35.046 --> 00:40:38.596
and I really wanted to take
part in telling that story

00:40:38.596 --> 00:40:41.456
and make her look visually
as cool as I possibly could.

00:40:42.106 --> 00:40:45.546
So this is good enough for
now, a good starting point.

00:40:45.546 --> 00:40:47.906
So I've painted into
this bump channel.

00:40:48.566 --> 00:40:52.056
And I can actually take
that channel and start

00:40:52.056 --> 00:40:53.466
to use it in the color.

00:40:53.466 --> 00:40:55.636
So when I visit that
channel here,

00:40:55.636 --> 00:40:57.786
I can multiply the color
just like in Photoshop.

00:40:58.106 --> 00:41:00.276
And we can start to see how
it will affect the final look

00:41:00.276 --> 00:41:00.836
of the character.

00:41:01.286 --> 00:41:02.636
But there's a whole
lot of other channels

00:41:02.666 --> 00:41:05.716
that are needed for
the final look.

00:41:05.896 --> 00:41:07.626
The first is the
specular channel.

00:41:07.626 --> 00:41:10.306
What this is, and I'm not going
to bother painting it today,

00:41:10.776 --> 00:41:14.976
what this is, is it's showing
where the shininess is,

00:41:14.976 --> 00:41:16.076
if that makes any sense.

00:41:16.076 --> 00:41:17.186
It's showing what
parts are going

00:41:17.186 --> 00:41:18.866
to be shinier than other parts.

00:41:19.276 --> 00:41:21.456
And then the roughness channel,
which makes it even less sense,

00:41:21.456 --> 00:41:23.386
is showing how glossy

00:41:23.386 --> 00:41:26.206
or how rough those specular
highlights are going to be.

00:41:26.966 --> 00:41:30.496
Now, as an artist, these
things don't make a whole lot

00:41:30.496 --> 00:41:31.476
of sense to me visually.

00:41:31.476 --> 00:41:33.316
I look at this gray
and I'm like, "OK.

00:41:33.976 --> 00:41:35.636
What does that mean, right?

00:41:35.636 --> 00:41:36.496
Her eyes are black.

00:41:36.496 --> 00:41:39.566
Her lips are a slightly
darker gray than her skin.

00:41:39.606 --> 00:41:40.856
Her color is this other gray.

00:41:41.266 --> 00:41:44.506
I don't know how that
affects the final look."

00:41:44.506 --> 00:41:47.076
And before a program like
MARI, I would have to load

00:41:47.076 --> 00:41:49.516
up these channels as
individual flattened images

00:41:49.796 --> 00:41:51.016
in a program like Photoshop.

00:41:51.356 --> 00:41:54.956
I'd paint the gray her of her
lips and hope that it was going

00:41:54.956 --> 00:41:57.116
to be the right shade of gray.

00:41:57.116 --> 00:41:58.866
And then I'd kick off a render,

00:41:58.996 --> 00:42:01.856
and that render would take
anywhere from two minutes

00:42:01.856 --> 00:42:05.016
for a really kind of
inexpensive render

00:42:05.016 --> 00:42:07.306
that shows me a vague idea
of what it's going to look

00:42:07.306 --> 00:42:11.036
like to a full 12-hour render if
I'm going into the actual shot

00:42:11.036 --> 00:42:13.166
from the film with all of the
lighting and all the bells

00:42:13.166 --> 00:42:14.046
and whistles turned on.

00:42:14.506 --> 00:42:17.156
So if I really wanted to see
how her lips looked in the shot,

00:42:17.586 --> 00:42:19.786
I would need to wait up
to 12 hours to see that.

00:42:19.786 --> 00:42:21.076
And so, I'd paint my gray.

00:42:21.656 --> 00:42:22.766
I'd save the image.

00:42:22.766 --> 00:42:23.856
I'd kick off the renders.

00:42:24.586 --> 00:42:25.326
And I would wait.

00:42:25.326 --> 00:42:27.556
And then I get to render
back and I go like, "OK,

00:42:27.556 --> 00:42:30.146
her lips are too
glossy," so I'd go back.

00:42:30.176 --> 00:42:32.016
I'd paint a slightly
darker gray.

00:42:32.416 --> 00:42:34.816
And then I'd send it and then
I'd realize I'd gone the wrong

00:42:34.816 --> 00:42:36.886
direction, and now her
lips are even shinier.

00:42:37.136 --> 00:42:38.726
And I'd wait another
12 hours, right?

00:42:38.726 --> 00:42:39.806
So, you can see how

00:42:39.806 --> 00:42:42.906
that iteration could completely
kill the creative process.

00:42:43.326 --> 00:42:45.776
What MARI allows us to do
is it allows us to take all

00:42:45.776 --> 00:42:49.376
of these separate kind
of nonsensical channels

00:42:49.786 --> 00:42:53.166
and create a shader that we can
actually preview in real time

00:42:53.496 --> 00:42:56.186
that lets us look at
what the final look

00:42:56.186 --> 00:42:58.656
of the character is going to
be in that finished render.

00:42:59.366 --> 00:43:02.276
And instead of waiting for
anywhere from 2 minutes

00:43:02.306 --> 00:43:06.356
to 12 hours, we can see that
at 60 frames per second.

00:43:07.186 --> 00:43:09.036
So I'm going to switch
over to her shader

00:43:10.116 --> 00:43:11.006
and turn on the lighting.

00:43:11.776 --> 00:43:14.616
And you can see here
how now we've got all

00:43:14.616 --> 00:43:15.506
of those different channels

00:43:15.506 --> 00:43:17.726
that I've painted
working at the same time.

00:43:18.166 --> 00:43:20.606
We've got those bumps that I
just painted, those wrinkles.

00:43:21.246 --> 00:43:22.136
We've got the color.

00:43:22.136 --> 00:43:25.366
And then the shininess, you
can see how her eyelid is much

00:43:25.476 --> 00:43:28.036
shinier than the
rest of her skin.

00:43:28.036 --> 00:43:30.986
And this is, you know, this
is possible, you know, again,

00:43:30.986 --> 00:43:32.926
through the hardware and the
software working together

00:43:32.926 --> 00:43:33.826
to give us this image.

00:43:34.366 --> 00:43:37.736
And if you think about it,
remember how I said that each

00:43:37.736 --> 00:43:40.626
of those frames was
8,000 pixel squared.

00:43:40.946 --> 00:43:43.516
Well there's nine of those
for every single channel.

00:43:43.676 --> 00:43:45.916
So for one channel,
the color channel,

00:43:45.916 --> 00:43:49.366
that's 600 million
pixels, all right,

00:43:49.486 --> 00:43:52.136
600 million points
of image data.

00:43:53.386 --> 00:43:56.506
Now we're looking at four
channels simultaneously which is

00:43:56.586 --> 00:44:00.106
about 2.4 billion
pixels, all right?

00:44:00.666 --> 00:44:02.146
That is a vast amount of data.

00:44:02.146 --> 00:44:04.756
That's 10 gigabytes
of image data.

00:44:05.196 --> 00:44:07.996
And MARI is letting us
preview that all in real time

00:44:08.496 --> 00:44:10.646
and it's running so
smoothly on this hardware.

00:44:10.726 --> 00:44:14.536
I've been working on MARI for
about two or three years now

00:44:14.576 --> 00:44:16.156
and I've never seen
it run smoother

00:44:16.236 --> 00:44:17.776
than it does on the new Mac Pro.

00:44:17.966 --> 00:44:20.626
By the way, so I've been
working on this for a couple

00:44:20.626 --> 00:44:22.976
of weeks now and it's
been in this giant box.

00:44:23.126 --> 00:44:26.816
I had no idea what it looked
like until yesterday, all right?

00:44:26.886 --> 00:44:27.296
No idea.

00:44:28.016 --> 00:44:29.606
[ Applause ]

00:44:29.606 --> 00:44:33.666
The funny thing was it could've
been the size of a mini fridge.

00:44:33.696 --> 00:44:34.846
I had no idea.

00:44:34.986 --> 00:44:35.856
Or an iPhone.

00:44:35.856 --> 00:44:37.676
We were thinking it was this
floating sphere, you know.

00:44:37.796 --> 00:44:38.596
I had no idea.

00:44:38.596 --> 00:44:40.986
But I just knew that it
was running really well.

00:44:40.986 --> 00:44:43.006
I just had no idea it was
inside this mystery box.

00:44:43.006 --> 00:44:47.906
So, it was just as exciting for
me yesterday as for you guys.

00:44:47.906 --> 00:44:49.066
Anyway, I lost my
train of thought.

00:44:49.176 --> 00:44:51.646
So here we are.

00:44:51.646 --> 00:44:52.826
We're looking at
all these shaders.

00:44:52.826 --> 00:44:55.526
Now, the great thing is even
though it's really pretty

00:44:55.526 --> 00:44:57.466
to see this shader in real time,

00:44:57.866 --> 00:45:00.516
here's where the actual
real advantage comes in.

00:45:01.696 --> 00:45:04.486
Working at an animation studio,
you paint all these details

00:45:04.486 --> 00:45:06.156
and then the animators
have to come in

00:45:06.156 --> 00:45:08.086
and start moving
stuff around, right?

00:45:08.086 --> 00:45:09.996
I mean the audacity of that.

00:45:10.206 --> 00:45:12.676
So, I paint the wrinkles on her

00:45:12.676 --> 00:45:16.336
and then once the character
actually is talking and moving,

00:45:16.336 --> 00:45:19.136
sometimes what I painted
doesn't look right anymore

00:45:19.136 --> 00:45:20.006
and I have to fix it.

00:45:20.006 --> 00:45:22.886
Now, in the past, it's really
hard to identify those problems

00:45:22.886 --> 00:45:24.256
or at least it takes
a lot of time

00:45:24.256 --> 00:45:27.086
because to render the animation,
I definitely need to wait

00:45:27.086 --> 00:45:28.636
at least a few hours
to see that.

00:45:29.236 --> 00:45:31.486
And if I want to see it in
the context of the shot,

00:45:31.886 --> 00:45:33.506
I would need to wait
up to 12 hours.

00:45:33.726 --> 00:45:37.906
So, MARI allows us to bring the
final animation from the shot

00:45:38.076 --> 00:45:40.516
into this environment so
I can actually preview it.

00:45:40.516 --> 00:45:42.816
So, I'm going to scrub
to her animation here.

00:45:42.816 --> 00:45:44.506
And this is the same
shot that I showed you.

00:45:44.786 --> 00:45:47.306
And you can see her
speaking and moving around.

00:45:47.366 --> 00:45:50.946
And I noticed at this point
where she raises eyebrow like,

00:45:50.946 --> 00:45:55.296
wow, OK, my textures are
stretching right there,

00:45:55.296 --> 00:45:55.666
all right?

00:45:55.666 --> 00:45:56.576
So let me fix that.

00:45:56.576 --> 00:45:58.636
So I'm going to go
to my bump channel.

00:45:58.636 --> 00:46:01.876
I'm going to pull in my
elephant texture again.

00:46:02.776 --> 00:46:05.836
And I'm going to
grab these wrinkles.

00:46:13.766 --> 00:46:15.186
And I can paint straight

00:46:15.296 --> 00:46:17.926
onto this animated frame,
right, in real time.

00:46:18.016 --> 00:46:19.096
[ Applause ]

00:46:19.096 --> 00:46:19.836
It's pretty cool, huh?

00:46:20.516 --> 00:46:23.906
[ Applause ]

00:46:24.406 --> 00:46:27.396
And now when I play the
animation, I can say, "OK,

00:46:27.516 --> 00:46:29.926
you know, how does it look, you
know, at this moment, right?

00:46:29.926 --> 00:46:32.586
How does it look, you
know, at any given frame?"

00:46:32.586 --> 00:46:35.496
And I've just identified
and fixed a problem

00:46:35.496 --> 00:46:37.766
in about 30 seconds that
would've typically taken me

00:46:37.766 --> 00:46:40.426
about 2 days before if I
were to wait for the full--

00:46:40.646 --> 00:46:42.246
all the bells and
whistles renders, right?

00:46:42.486 --> 00:46:43.676
And that is fantastic.

00:46:43.676 --> 00:46:47.336
It is-- you know, I'm able
to work ridiculously faster

00:46:47.336 --> 00:46:48.666
in an environment like this.

00:46:48.746 --> 00:46:53.176
And it is, you know,
again-- so, like I said,

00:46:53.176 --> 00:46:55.556
MARI has never run faster than
I've seen it on this machine.

00:46:55.626 --> 00:46:57.346
And we can push the
limits of that.

00:46:57.346 --> 00:47:00.636
So, this character represents
about 10 gigabytes worth

00:47:00.636 --> 00:47:02.606
of image data but we
can do more than that.

00:47:02.696 --> 00:47:07.956
I can bring in Mike Wazowski
which essentially doubles it

00:47:07.956 --> 00:47:09.916
to about 20 gigabytes
because he's got his own set

00:47:09.916 --> 00:47:10.546
